question: Rostker v. Goldberg held that the practice of what way of filling armed forces vacancies was consitutional?

The practice of filling armed forces vacancies through conscription (the draft) is constitutional, as upheld by the Supreme Court in the case of Rostker v. Goldberg [Data: Reports (1)]. This decision was based on the power granted to Congress under Article I, Section 8, Clause 12 of the U.S. Constitution, which gives them the authority to raise and support armies.

In the case of Rostker v. Goldberg, it was argued that the All-Volunteer Force Act of 1973, which ended the draft, discriminated against women because only men were required to register for the draft. However, the Supreme Court ruled that this differential treatment was justified by the military's need for a selective service system that could efficiently and effectively meet its needs [Data: Reports (2)].

It is important to note that this ruling does not mean that conscription is the only way to fill armed forces vacancies. The U.S. has used an all-volunteer force since 1973, and this decision does not preclude Congress from changing the method of filling these vacancies in the future [Data: Reports (3)].

However, if conscription were to be reinstated, it would have to comply with the principles established in Rostker v. Goldberg. This includes being a selective service system that can efficiently and effectively meet the needs of the armed forces, and not discriminating against any group based on gender or other factors [Data: Reports (4)].

In summary, the practice of filling armed forces vacancies through conscription is constitutional, as upheld by the Supreme Court in Rostker v. Goldberg.
